04585nam a2200625Ia 9781501729041DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017290417 a10.7591/97815017290412doi  a(DE-B1597)515221  a(OCoLC)1100452635  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.891/40729832211 aMunasinghe, Viranjini P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCallaloo or Tossed Salad? :bEast Indians and the Cultural Politics of Identity in Trinidad /cViranjini P. Munasinghe. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b4 maps, 2 line drawings, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t[1] Introduction -- t[2] Ethnicity and Nation -- t[3] Foretelling Ethnicity: East Indians between Ex-Slaves and Planters -- t[4] Situating Ethnicity: East Indians against the Nation -- t[5] To Be Ethnic in a Place in Between -- t[6] To Be Mixed Up in a Place in Between -- t[7] Nation Building within the State: Consolidating an Afro-Caribbean Nation -- t[8] Breaking the Silence: The Disintegration of Hegemonic Rule -- t[9] Redefining the National Image -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCallaloo or Tossed Salad? is a historical and ethnographic case study of the politics of cultural struggle between two traditionally subordinate ancestral groups in Trinidad, those claiming African and Indian descent. Viranjini Munasinghe argues that East Indians in Trinidad seek to become a legitimate part of the nation by redefining what it means to be Trinidadian, not by changing what it means to be Indian. In her view, Indo-Trinidadians' recent and ongoing struggle for national and cultural identity builds from dissatisfaction with the place they were originally assigned within Trinidadian society. The author examines how Indo-Trinidadian leaders in Trinidad have come to challenge the implicit claim that their ethnic identity is antithetical to their national identity. Their political and cultural strategy seeks to change the national image of Trinidad by introducing Indian elements alongside those of the dominant Afro-Caribbean (Creole) culture.Munasinghe analyzes a number of broad theoretical issues: the moral, political, and cultural dimensions of identity; the relation between ethnicity and the nation; and the possible autonomy of New World nationalisms from European forms. She details how principles of exclusion continue to operate in nationalist projects that celebrate ancestral diversity and multiculturalism. Drawing on the insights of theorists who use creolization to understand the emergence of Afro-American cultures, Munasinghe argues that Indo-Trinidadians can be considered Creole because they, like Afro-Trinidadians, are creators and not just bearers of culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEast IndianszTrinidad and TobagoxEthnic identity. 0aEast IndianszTrinidad and TobagoxPolitics and government. 4aAnthropology. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172904140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501729041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501729041/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles